Ideas for improving epistemics in AI safety outreachPublished on August 21, 2023 7:55 PM GMT<br/><br/><p> 2022 年和 2023 年，人们越来越关注招募人才来致力于减轻人工智能带来的潜在生存风险。例如，我们看到致力于向人们介绍人工智能带来的生存风险问题的大学俱乐部、务虚会和研讨会的数量有所增加。</p><p>然而，这些努力可能会营造一个认知不太理想的环境。考虑到让人们为人工智能安全做出积极贡献的目标，我们有动力关注这一点，而不必过多担心我们的论点是否可靠。许多从事现场建设的人并不是人工智能安全或机器学习领域的专家，而是因为相信人工智能安全是一个重要问题而受到激励。一些参与者可能认为解决与人工智能相关的风险很重要，但没有完全理解这一信念背后的推理或进行了强烈的反驳。</p><p>这篇文章是对这个问题的简要审查，并提出了一些改善外展工作认知的想法。</p><p><i>注：</i>我于 2022 年 12 月首次起草了这份草案。从那时起，主流中越来越多地讨论了对人工智能 x 风险的担忧，因此人工智能安全领域的构建者应该希望少用一些奇怪的、认知上不佳的论点。尽管如此，在<a href="https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/euzDpFvbLqPdwCnXF/university-ea-groups-need-fixing">最近的一篇文章</a>指出 EA 社区建设中的认识论不佳之后，我认为认识论仍然值得讨论。</p><h1>人工智能安全领域建设在哪些方面可能在认知上不健康？</h1><ul><li>组织者可能会提出有关人工智能安全的论点，这些论点可能（相对*）令人信服但存在缺陷<ul><li>推进人工智能安全重要性的论点，同时忽视反对论点<ul><li>例如，引用 x% 的研究人员认为人工智能有 y% 的机会造成一场生存灾难，而不需要警告专家们有广泛不同的观点</li></ul></li><li>自信地提出有缺陷或前提不充分的论点<ul><li>例如，声称工具收敛是不可避免的，假设人工智能正在最大化奖励（参见<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/pdaGN6pQyQarFHXF4/reward-is-not-the-optimization-target"><u>奖励不是优化目标</u></a>，尽管也有评论不同意这一点）</li></ul></li><li>另请参阅：Rohin Shah <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/bkpZHXMJx3dG5waA7/ways-to-buy-time?commentId=jropYhtAW72zfHRBr"><u>在此</u></a>发表的评论，其中提到很少有人能够为人工智能 x 风险的研究提出论点，而他认为这显然是有缺陷的</li><li>*同时，我认为大多数机器学习人员并不认为人工智能安全论点特别引人注目。</li></ul></li><li>人们很容易认为支持人工智能安全的论点“应该”是更正确的。人们可能会对表达不同意见感到犹豫。</li><li>在阅读小组（例如基于<a href="https://aisafetyfundamentals.com/">人工智能安全基础知识</a>的阅读小组）中，人们可能会同意阅读材料中的论点或讨论主持人所说的内容 - 服从权威，并且对于自己思考论点犹豫不决。</li><li>人们可能会参加阅读小组，但只是浏览一下阅读材料，然后在不理解论点的情况下就相信结论而离开；或者注意到他们很困惑，但不管相信结论还是走开。</li></ul><h1>为什么好的认知很有价值？</h1><ul><li>为了进行富有成效的研究，我们希望避免对人工智能 x 风险的理解存在明显缺陷<ul><li>“不正确的论点会导致错误的信念，从而导致无用的解决方案”（ <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/bkpZHXMJx3dG5waA7/ways-to-buy-time?commentId=jropYhtAW72zfHRBr"><u>来自 Rohin Shah</u></a> ）</li></ul></li><li>糟糕的论点不利于说服人们（或者至少，如果你无法预见 ML 社区的常见反对意见，这似乎很糟糕）</li><li>人们提出错误的论点不利于人们做有用的工作</li><li>吸引更多具有良好认知的人</li></ul><p>为了认识论的严谨性，我还将就为什么认识论可能被高估提出一些可能的论点。</p><ul><li>也许人们可以做有用的工作，即使他们不了解人工智能安全为何重要或什么技术议程重要的内部观点。</li><li>可能有人最终会感到困惑并且没有采取任何有用的行动。</li><li>其他活动可能相对更有价值。</li><li>认知可能已经足够好了。</li><li>一致性研究人员在很多事情上存在分歧，并且可能不清楚你不同意的人是否有“糟糕的认知”或者只是有不同的模型/先验。</li></ul><h1>改善认知的想法</h1><ul><li>接受关于人工智能为何可能危险的更现代、更有根据的论点<ul><li>我认为 2000 年代和 2010 年代的许多人工智能 x 风险论点并不适合当前基于大型语言模型的人工智能代理范例。 《<a href="https://www.safe.ai/ai-risk">灾难性人工智能风险概述</a>》似乎比<i>《超级智能</i>》更接地气，《<a href="https://course.aisafetyfundamentals.com/governance">人工智能治理课程》</a>的入门读物似乎比（当前的） <a href="https://course.aisafetyfundamentals.com/alignment">《人工智能调整课程》</a>更强<i>。</i></li></ul></li><li>会议期间进行朗读，让与会者更好地理解内容<ul><li>这还有其他一些好处，例如：您可以记住要讨论的具体要点</li></ul></li><li>可能提供理性研讨会<ul><li>当你感到困惑时请注意</li><li>注意：理性研讨会不应该是为了让人们认真对待非常规想法；他们实际上应该有针对性地帮助改善认知</li></ul></li><li>积极检查参与者对内容的理解，并检查他们是否能够提出支持或反对的有力论据<ul><li>这可能看起来像：开始讨论，要求某人总结论点</li></ul></li><li>不要以说服别人为目的进行对话<ul><li>我更愿意重新调整努力，鼓励/支持有动力的人申请机会</li></ul></li><li>积极邀请人们提出不同意见，也许可以探索他们的想法<ul><li>注意：我不想要一个人们在没有任何阻力的情况下表达想法（即使很糟糕）的 kumbaya 环境。</li></ul></li><li>与更广泛的 ML 社区保持联系（例如，在 Twitter 上关注他们、参加 AI 活动）</li></ul><br/><br/> <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/SDpaZ7MdH5yRnobrZ/ideas-for-improving-epistemics-in-ai-safety-outreach#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/SDpaZ7MdH5yRnobrZ/ideas-for-improving-epistemics-in-ai-safety-outreach SDpaZ7MdH5yRnobrZmic Mon, 21 Aug 2023 19:55:46 GMT 
Large Language Models will be Great for CensorshipPublished on August 21, 2023 7:03 PM GMT<br/><br/><p><i>作为</i><a href="https://serimats.org/"><i><u>SERI ML 对齐理论学者计划</u></i></a><i>- 2023 年夏季队列</i>的一部分制作</p><p><i>感谢</i><a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/users/ev_"><i>ev_</i></a><i>和</i><a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/users/kei-1"><i>Kei</i></a><i>对本文提出的建议。</i></p><p>法学硕士可以做许多令人难以置信的事情。他们可以生成独特的创意内容，就任意数量的主题进行长时间对话，完成复杂的认知任务，并撰写几乎任何论点。更世俗的是，它们现在是执行无聊分类任务的最先进技术，因此有能力从根本上提升全世界独裁政权的审查能力。</p><h2>审查制度如何运作</h2><p>在具有广泛审查制度的极权政府国家——<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Censorship_in_the_Russian_Empire">沙皇俄罗斯</a>、<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Censorship_in_East_Germany">东欧共产主义国家</a>、<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Censorship_in_China">中华人民共和国</a>、<a href="https://www.sahistory.org.za/sites/default/files/DC/remar82.3/remar82.3.pdf">实行种族隔离的南非</a>等——所有公共材料最好都由政府工作人员阅读和审查，以确保它们不包含任何可能冒犯人民的内容。政权。众所周知，这项任务极其无聊，审查员经常会错过明显具有颠覆性的材料，因为他们懒得检查所有内容。<a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2493377">马克思的<i>《资本论》</i>被认为是无趣的经济学，因此在 1890 年代合法进入俄罗斯</a>。</p><p>旧式的审查制度不可能规模化，审查机构施加控制的真正方式是通过威慑和恐惧，而不是对传播的实际控制。没有人知道他们不能跨越的严格边界线，因此他们远离它。轻微地批评政府目前不受欢迎的一小部分也许是可以接受的，但为什么要把你的整个未来拿在可能毫无结果的投诉上呢？在一些政权中，例如毛泽东领导下的中华人民共和国，混乱的内部进程导致可接受的表达方式不断逆转，到文化大革命结束时，大多数人已经认识到，保持安静就是最安全的道路<span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefsy9d7paqgz"><sup><a href="#fnsy9d7paqgz">[1]</a></sup></span> 。审查制度可以防止公众有组织的抵抗，对于政权来说，理想的情况是，这会导致对现有权力的默许，但默默怨恨的民众并不安全。当革命最终到来时，全体人民可能会立即释放所有压抑的愤怒，转而攻击他们的统治者。每个人都知道每个人都知道每个人都讨厌政府，即使他们只能在私人可信渠道中承认这一点。</p><p>由于适当的普遍和全面的监视一直是不切实际的，因此政权转而将重点放在更有针对性的干预措施上，以防止潜在的颠覆。秘密警察依赖的是有针对性的线人网络，而不是能够监听每分钟对话录音的工作人员。这产生了可怕而令人不寒而栗的效果，摧毁了许多人的生命，但也没有达到应有的效果。主要抵抗运动领导人仍然能够在极权国家中出现，一旦政府表现出真正软弱的迹象，半组织的持不同政见者就会准备抓住时机<span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefvhnjiyrwqg"><sup><a href="#fnvhnjiyrwqg">[2]</a></sup></span> 。</p><h2>数字通信和难以捉摸的全面审查制度</h2><p>传统的审查制度主要针对数量相对较少的出版作品：报纸、书籍、电影、广播、电视。只需使用人力，这在某种程度上是可以管理的。然而，在过去的二十年里，潜在公开的交流和材料的数量已经随着互联网而改变。</p><p>了解政府如何处理新数据要困难得多，因为我们掌握的信息主要来自监视的受害者，他们与过去一样处于威慑性恐惧之中。如果受害者想象国家比实际更有能力，那就意味着国家正在成功，并且更难评估其真实能力。我们没有来自内部人士的可靠说法或档案访问，因为在此期间没有主要政权倒台。</p><p>抛开这些警告不谈，政府审查最前沿的报道相当令人担忧。目前的中华人民共和国政府显然愿意投入巨资对其认为具有潜在颠覆性的人口进行极端监控和控制。据新疆报道，人们的手机经常受到搜查，包括公共社交媒体账户和私人信息。没有什么是安全的，在镇压穆斯林少数民族的初期，人们不确定哪些渠道受到监控，哪些渠道没有受到监控。值得注意的是，在这些账户中，国家似乎希望找到任何可能具有颠覆性的内容，但在频繁的检查中，只是错过了明显令人反感的内容。达伦·拜勒 (Darren Byler) 的消息来源报道称，虽然检查站的警卫会检查他的微信，但他们似乎不确定如何使用外国社交媒体应用程序或注意到他使用了 VPN <span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefy4p8vmgi2hl"><sup><a href="#fny4p8vmgi2hl">[3]</a></sup></span> 。一切仍然会受到许多层人为错误的影响，在不使用高压暴力和拘留（他们已经采取的手段）的情况下对新疆进行全面监视的任务似乎超出了中华人民共和国国家的能力，尽管他们已经投入了大量资金这个黑暗任务。</p><p>我们还知道，现代互联网平台的建立是为了对信息进行集中控制，但这些工具远非完美。任何有关天安门事件的提及都被严格隐藏在防火墙内的中文来源中，尽管例如英文维基百科的文章几年前就可以公开访问。微信和其他中国社交媒体平台似乎受到严格控制：<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Peng_Shuai">彭帅对一名党内官员的指控很快就从可访问的来源中删除</a>，<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhao_Wei">赵薇</a>的整个职业生涯也很快消失了。虽然这些都是极其反乌托邦和令人不安的，但值得注意的是，人们可以看到这些事件与许多愤怒的中国公民一起实时发生。当局可以在此类事件发生后不久遏制和控制，但不能等到事件爆发到足以需要进行人工针对人类的审查之前。一旦发生人工干预，自动流程就会防止相同的主题再次出现，但新事件似乎经常逃脱分类。</p><p>我们从更加开放的世界中的科技媒体公司了解到的情况证实了这一点。 Facebook、Twitter 和类似平台似乎拥有一套庞大的算法工具，可以防止被视为有毒的主题获得广泛影响或被看到，但这些工具都没有完美地发挥作用。互联网还彻底改变了扰乱或冒犯公众的内容的输出，如果平台希望最大化其用户和广告收入，则必须隐藏这些内容。 <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/31/technology/facebook-accenture-content-moderation.html"><u>大量劳动力对攻击性内容进行半手动标记</u></a>——东方集团无聊的审查员的继任者——现在至少能够保持通信基本无攻击性，并根据公司意识形态进行一些过滤。他们必须费力地浏览可怕的内容，并对模棱两可和不断变化的指导方针做出反应，但他们似乎让这些平台可以忍受。这些手动分类几乎肯定会被用来训练人工智能系统，但目前还没有迹象表明人类可以被取代。需要严厉、高度可见的人工干预的病毒式政治事件仍然经常发生。</p><h2> LLM 可以做什么？</h2><p>个人通信已完全数字化，但潜在颠覆性内容的算法分类尚未跟上网络媒体令人难以置信的规模。法学硕士可能是改变这一现状的工具，至少在文本领域是如此。如果过去的懒惰审查员只是让可扩展的法学硕士对每一篇文本的潜在风险和影响进行评分，他们就会变得更加懒惰和更加有效。</p><p>例如，可以简单地指示 GPT-4 扮演沙皇审查员的角色。为了在简单的提示下测试它，我给了它尼古拉·车尔尼雪夫斯基的小说<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/What_Is_to_Be_Done%3F_(novel)"><i>《做什么？》</i></a>中的段落。这部 1863 年的俄罗斯小说因启发了许多著名的社会主义者和革命家而闻名，尤其是列宁，他非常珍视这部作品。它也因审查制度的失败而闻名——车尔尼雪夫斯基作为政治犯写了这本书，小说在向公众发布之前经过了监狱审查和出版审查。</p><p>在一段关于主角挣扎的段落中，审查系统没有发现任何问题：</p><p> <a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f3385b2-0df6-4fc8-9cdc-76f773e2aa9d_1600x590.png 1456w"></a></p><p></p><p>然而，鉴于有关裁缝公社的一段话启发了许多读者，它指出了潜在的颠覆性危险：</p><p> <a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F662a21ef-c9fb-4049-af31-c33edf8ff8f2_1600x598.png 1456w"></a></p><p></p><p>像这样的简单提示不够强大，并且可能会捕获太多误报。但即使是这个极其简单的系统也可以节省人类审查员大量的时间，并且对于此类作品可能会导致不同的结果。</p><p>大的上下文窗口可能会使任务变得更加容易。 Claude 100k 能够处理大约一半的小说，并提供审查员可能发送给主管的那种报告，其质量可能优于俄罗斯国家当时制作的报告。</p><p> <a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3e31cf27-a945-47df-aa0f-8c386a304e9d_1228x1228.png 1456w"></a></p><p></p><p>而这只花了几秒钟的时间。审查沙皇国家最后一个世纪在俄罗斯出版的每一部小说都可以在几个小时内完成，我敢打赌，受过适当指导的克劳德会比俄罗斯审查人员在整个职业生涯中写出更好的报告。</p><p>就成本而言，法学硕士将是迄今为止最有效的审查工具。举个例子，要阅读 120,000 个单词（根据《纽约时报》一天发布的内容的粗略估计），快速阅读器以每分钟 300 个单词的速度大约需要六个小时<span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefkmlpvsro7iq"><sup><a href="#fnkmlpvsro7iq">[4]</a></sup></span> 。对这些进行分类和评论可能需要更多时间。将所有这些文本输入 GPT-4 需要 7.2 美元，ChatGPT 需要 0.36 美元，他们几乎立即完成，法学硕士的进步将推动这一过程变得越来越便宜，直到没有每小时工资可以竞争。</p><p>法学硕士的速度是无法比拟的，而即时、实时审查的可能性可能会催生一种新的审查制度。 I would suspect such LLM systems will be used to flag any potential subversive material before they have the chance to spread. An extra few seconds before a post goes live could save companies huge risks, so they will likely have an AI review process which can be double checked by a human in cases of ambiguity. Messages both private and public will be monitored and can be intercepted before they are read. Updates to the classification system might make old messages disappear without announcement.</p><p> LLMs may not fully replace censors, but will make them orders of magnitude more effective. Humans will still have to manage the AIs to program in the changing and contradictory standards of censorship, but the AIs will do all the evaluation themselves. The sort of slightly ambiguous instructions that <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona"><u>Facebook moderators are given</u></a> are the sort of classification tasks that LLMs succeed at which no previous NLP system could manage <span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefr10ctwy4j89"><sup><a href="#fnr10ctwy4j89">[5]</a></sup></span> . I would expect censorship bureaus in totalitarian states are given similar tasks for more obviously bad ends. It was not feasible to give humans the enormous and boring task of evaluating every communication of every person and thinking hard about potential subversive externalities. But with AI, this dream of total surveillance is now feasible and likely to come upon us quite soon.</p><p> There will be limits, especially as so much of communication is now done in the form of video and images. We are still likely a little bit off from a system which can understand purely visual content perfectly. But automatic transcription of words in audio and images will allow LLMs to intervene in this domain as well.</p><p> Crucially, censorship does not actually have to be accurate to work. If these systems are not good and flag plenty of innocuous content as subversive, from the regime&#39;s perspective this is fine. People will grumble and learn to steer around the systems, and the goal of creating acceptance of the regime will have been achieved.</p><p> If better LLM classifications of content are implemented at every level, the effects are not really predictable, and it is quite possible that regimes will overplay their hand. If Chinese users of WeChat attempt to let off steam about dealing with government bureaucracy to their friends and an LLM classifier prevents this content from even being sent in the first place, or modifies it to be innocuous on the way, what will be the overall political effect? People might conform and simply stop discussing politics or questioning the powers that be. But they also might take their previously digital conversations into other channels, creating conversational standards more resistant to surveillance and possibly more dangerous to the state. Totalitarian regimes are brutal and terrifying and murderous, but they are not always competent.</p><h2> What Comes Next</h2><p> It has widely been reported that the PRC <a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2023/03/03/china-censors-chatbots-artificial-intelligence/"><u>may be hesitant to deploy public-facing LLMs due to concerns that the models themselves can&#39;t be adequately censored</u></a> - it might be very difficult to make a version of ChatGPT that cannot be tricked into saying “4/6/89.” But I would suspect that the technology itself, especially in the versions being made by state-aligned corporations, is likely to eventually make it into the censorship and surveillance pipeline. These will be used to classify and regulate messages and media as they are being sent, as well as possibly to comb through and understand masses of collected data. While there are plenty of internal bureaucratic reasons that might slow or even prevent this process, I would suspect that enterprising censors or tech companies will eventually give this a try.</p><p> Other existing totalitarian regimes may not be as fast, though may follow. Economic incentives can end up leading to increased development of such systems in the PRC, where there is significant government demand, <a href="https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Exporting-the-surveillance-state-via-trade-in-AI_FINAL-1.pdf"><u>followed by the export to other autocratic states</u></a> . Russia may be an early adopter, but it is not clear. North Korea, Cuba, or the communist regimes in Southeast Asia don&#39;t have the same levels of digital sophistication as the PRC but still could follow. Saudi Arabia and other states with an interest in technical sophistication and the suppression of dissent might also be likely to use these systems. Certain censorious factions in democratic countries such as India or Turkey could end up using such systems as well. And these techniques will likely be independently discovered and deployed by tech companies throughout the first world, especially in the United States.</p><p> There are two major applications corporate actors in the United States are likely to use censorship classification systems for. One is for the thorny and highly controversial area of content moderation, where the applications are obvious although the effects are uncertain. The other is for self-censorship both in compliance to incentives in relationships with totalitarian powers (mostly the PRC) and for avoiding general controversy in their home cultures. I believe that such systems are already being used by firms deploying LLMs as a safeguard against negative attention and I would expect the use of such systems to expand to all public-facing communication as a safety mechanism.</p><p> There is no real way to prevent this. It is only a matter of time before well-resourced state actors begin implementing and advancing such systems. Mitigations, such as techniques that can consistently fool LLMs and are difficult to patch, would be a worthy area for research although they might have other externalities as well. Further capabilities advances that might affect this problem should be considered in this light before deployment. </p><ol class="footnotes" role="doc-endnotes"><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnsy9d7paqgz"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefsy9d7paqgz">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Frank Dikötter&#39;s <i>People&#39;s Trilogy</i> contains a lot of such examples. The purest illustration of why it is better to stay quiet is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hundred_Flowers_Campaign">Hundred Flowers Campaign</a> and its after. For how learned silence can actually undermine regime goals, the chapter &quot;The Silent Revolution&quot; in <i>The Cultural Revolution</i> is recommended.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnvhnjiyrwqg"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefvhnjiyrwqg">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Eastern bloc Europe is full of these stories, one notable one being Václav Havel https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V%C3%A1clav_Havel#Political_dissident</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fny4p8vmgi2hl"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefy4p8vmgi2hl">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Darren Byler, <i>In the Camps</i> , page 47.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnkmlpvsro7iq"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefkmlpvsro7iq">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> Estimates are inexact and based on quick searches for average length of New York Times article, amount of articles published per day, and adult reading speed.</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnr10ctwy4j89"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefr10ctwy4j89">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> From the article:</p><p> “A post calling someone &#39;my favorite n-----&#39; is allowed to stay up, because under the policy it is considered “explicitly positive content.”</p><p> &#39;Autistic people should be sterilized&#39; seems offensive to him, but it stays up as well. Autism is not a &#39;protected characteristic&#39; the way race and gender are, and so it doesn&#39;t violate the policy. (&#39;Men should be sterilized&#39; would be taken down.)”</p><p> Assessing sentiment in complex circumstances and screening for particular protected characteristics seem within reach of GPT systems whereas earlier NLP approaches may not have been accurate enough.</p></div></li></ol><br/><br/> <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/oqvsR2LmHWamyKDcj/large-language-models-will-be-great-for-censorship#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/oqvsR2LmHWamyKDcj/large-language-models-will-be-great-for-censorship oqvsR2LmHWamyKDcjEthan Edwards Mon, 21 Aug 2023 19:41:47 GMT 
"Throwing Exceptions" Is A Strange Programming PatternPublished on August 21, 2023 6:50 PM GMT<br/><br/><p> For laypeople: In software, “throwing an exception” is a programmer-chosen type of behavior that occurs on the event that an “error” occurs in the course of program execution. This might happen immediately prior to or right at the time of the error.</p><p> This is ostensibly done in order to avoid something more catastrophic happening down the line. I&#39;m going to argue that this basis does not often seem to be justified.</p><p> You are probably familiar with instances of your programs suddenly and without warning becoming unresponsive, closing themselves down, or simply straight-up disappearing sometimes, perhaps with an error message pop-up soon to follow, but perhaps without one. These are due to exceptions being thrown, not just “errors” per se.让我解释。</p><p> When a function or procedure is called in a program, it is typically expected to return something. The value that this function returns is going to be either one of a set of “normal” values, which are the ones you expect to receive if all goes well, or it could be an “abnormal” or “anomalous” value that only returns if “something bad” happens.</p><p> If you choose to be relatively laid-back about your program, you might decide to check for anomalous values only <i>after</i> the procedure returns. Maybe even well after! Furthermore, how you choose to decide what “anomalous” means is arbitrary and up to you.</p><p> If you are more paranoid, you have typically decided what counts as “anomalous” before the program runs. These stipulations often come in the form of establishing type requirements for the arguments to the function, and possibly also range checks on the size or values of the inputs. These are just common examples, but like I said, it is arbitrary. It&#39;s also possible that the function calls another function inside of itself, awaits for that function to return something, and then decides whether or not what that function returned is anomalous.</p><p> “Throwing” or “raising” an exception occurs when you decide that your function will <i>immediately exit</i> and return a special error value instead, which may also try to indicate what type of error it is. If this function is called from another function, it passes this value “up the call stack.” The calling function, if it implements similar behavior (which is usually does), will pass that value or perhaps a different one (but still an error-value) up its call stack as well. If all of the calling functions implement such behavior, it will propagate all the way to the top, ending the program.</p><p> The only time it won&#39;t immediately end the program is if you decide to “catch” the exception, which means simply deal with the error and move on. However, this still causes the program to execute a different portion of code than it otherwise would. Also, this is somewhat language-specific.</p><p> So, the problematic behavior is the immediate exit. To see why this is a weird thing to do, imagine what would happen if it did not immediately exit in all cases. My guess is that, in the general case, your function would return gibberish. Your full program most likely would either keep running forever, run but produce garbled noise or gibberish, or run until some other termination conditions were met (user input, timer, or iterations max out).</p><p> So, why is that worse than immediately exiting on its own as soon as anomalous behavior is detected? Well, I don&#39;t think it can be worse in all cases. But when is it worse? It certainly must exceed a high bar for overall disutility caused. When you immediately terminate the program, you are most likely throwing away any work done up until that point, and certainly any amount of work that would have been done after that. It requires you to re-run the program probably from the beginning, but at the very least from immediately prior to the function call at which the exception was raised.</p><p> So that disutility must be overcome by the disutility of <i>incorrect</i> work done. That will depend on how incorrect the work done is, how difficult it is to detect, and - if that work has to be passed on to someone or something else later on - how badly that would affect the subsequent processes or tasks.</p><p> Regarding this feature in language design, Stroustrup mentions that this <i>could</i> be a language choice and that he believes it is better for the immediate exit to occur by default <span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefnrivk8c6zq"><sup><a href="#fnnrivk8c6zq">[1]</a></sup></span> :</p><blockquote><p> Should it be possible for an exception handler to decide to resume execution from the point of the exception? Some languages, such as PL/I and Mesa, say yes and reference 11 contains a concise argument for resumption in the context of C++. However, we feel it is a bad idea and the designers of Clu, Modula2+, Modula3, and ML agree.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p> Resumption is of only limited use without some means of correcting the situation that led to the exception. However, correcting error conditions after they occur is generally much harder than detecting them beforehand. Consider, for example, an exception handler trying to correct an error condition by changing some state variable. Code executed in the function call chain that led from the block with the handler to the function that threw the exception might have made decisions that depended on that state variable. This would leave the program in a state that was impossible without exception handling; that is, we would have introduced a brand new kind of bug that is very nasty and hard to find. In general, it is much safer to re-try the operation that failed from the exception handler than to resume the operation at the point where the exception was thrown.</p></blockquote><p> My understanding is that different contexts, have, in practice, caused different protocols to be followed.<span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefc1bnrtb73"><sup><a href="#fnc1bnrtb73">[2]</a></sup></span> For example, high-reliability code used in avionics software is said not to use exceptions, because it is worse for the airplane&#39;s engines to shut down upon an error being detected than for them to keep running even if there is a malfunction or abnormality somewhere.</p><p> That&#39;s kind of obvious. However, what is not obvious - to me at least - is why a <i>high-reliability</i> context would justify <i>less</i> “exception throwing” behavior. At first glance, it would seem that “exception throwing” would normally be done the more risk-averse one is. By default, the “immediate termination” behavior of exceptions implies that the programmer is trying to avoid the risk of greater damage being caused from uncertainty in the outcome of the program when anomalous data is fed into subsequent function calls and processes.</p><p> When I was personally involved in writing a machine learning library codebase, I was presented with the option of using thrown exceptions in many places. Typically, these exceptions would most likely be thrown within the functions that implemented a “node” in a model-graph (eg, a neural network or directed acyclic graph). These nodes depended on receiving input data and being able to perform accurate calculations on such data. Given that these functions had to be agnostic about what data would be received in the most general case, it is always possible that they would return values that were anomalous or undesirable in some way (eg, null or numeric overflow).</p><p> During testing (which includes testing while running on real data, not just unit tests), it was often much easier to allow the full processing of a model to occur rather than have exceptions thrown, which often clog up the log files or immediately shut down the program. One thing we realized is that nodes should still be able to work correctly even if nodes preceding them do not. This is more-or-less what I think of when I think of “resilience”: Even if a piece of your program (or model, in this case) is broken, the program is only roughly around as broken as the percentage of pieces that are broken in it. When we allowed our software to run without stopping, we could also reliably and more quickly get better data about which parts of it weren&#39;t working.</p><p> At the end of the day, your goal is to be able to correct issues and deploy the product quickly, as well as deliver results - hopefully incrementally more and better results. We were in a “high reliability” context as well: The answers had to be correct, but if they weren&#39;t (which you know you couldn&#39;t be sure about), they had to be at least well-calibrated answers.</p><p> So what brings about the opposite context, in which this “high-reliability” frame does not seem to apply?</p><p> One (speculative) explanation I have heard is that exceptions are used more routinely in software-business environments which involve contracts made between two parties (often both businesses). These contracts are often designed in a somewhat adversarial manner. In other words, the customer usually has somewhat of an asymmetric advantage over the vendor (especially if the latter is a small startup). Therefore, the customer has more power over the contract itself, and whether the startup survives at all may depend on whether these contracts are fulfilled to the letter.</p><p> Thus, it typically becomes more risky for the vendor&#39;s software to provide a potentially malformed product than it is for the vendor to simply delay the satisfaction of the service. The contracts signed between the provider-of-services and the receiver-of-services may stipulate that the latter will be entitled to more damages if the services fail to meet specific standards. However, those damages may be worse if the customer is under the impression that the vendor is adequately providing services for a specific period of time, when in fact they might not be.</p><p> Generally speaking, this is simply the idea that a job poorly-done is worse than one not even started. When people are worried about reputation and embarrassments and things like that, that will typically exacerbate the problem.</p><p> I&#39;m not sure if I agree that a job poorly-done is worse than one not even started. Not inherently, anyway. And if it is a reaction to one&#39;s social context and pressures one faces, I am also not sure that I agree bending to such pressure is actually even either the most personally-beneficial nor even the most utilitarian thing to do.</p><p> The problem seems to be at least somewhat inherently philosophical, but not intractable. My experience philosophically dealing with the problem of “errors <span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnref6vs6myakltk"><sup><a href="#fn6vs6myakltk">[3]</a></sup></span> ” leads me to believe that this might be in the same class as similar social-problems that I have been writing about lately. If so, that may mean there is some low-hanging fruit here in the sense of potentially being able to correct bigger issues that have yet to be resolved. </p><ol class="footnotes" role="doc-endnotes"><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnnrivk8c6zq"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefnrivk8c6zq">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> https://www.stroustrup.com/except89.pdf</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnc1bnrtb73"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefc1bnrtb73">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> https://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2019/p1947r0.pdf</p><blockquote><p> There have always been applications for which the use of exceptions was unsuitable. Examples Include:</p><ul><li> Systems where the memory is so limited that the run-time support needed for exception handling crowds out needed application functionality.</li><li> Hard-real time systems where the tool chains cannot guarantee prompt response after a throw. That is not an inherent language problem.</li><li> Systems relying on multiple unreliable computers so that immediate crash-and-restart is a reasonable (and almost necessary) way of dealing with errors that cannot be handled locally.</li></ul></blockquote></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fn6vs6myakltk"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnref6vs6myakltk">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p> As an issue that gets progressively escalated by someone noticing an error and raising a new one on top of it, which itself becomes a risk for someone else to avoid.</p></div></li></ol><br/><br/> <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/pnkLv8e8PTngsMMmr/throwing-exceptions-is-a-strange-programming-pattern#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/pnkLv8e8PTngsMMmr/throwing-exceptions-is-a-strange-programming-pattern pnkLv8e8PTngsMMmrThoth Hermes Mon, 21 Aug 2023 19:16:10 GMT 
Which possible AI systems are relatively safe?Published on August 21, 2023 5:00 PM GMT<br/><br/><p>据推测，某些类型的人工智能系统、架构、方法以及<i>从机器学习模型构建复杂系统的方式</i>比其他系统、架构、方法和方式更安全或更易于协调。保持功能不变，您会更高兴看到某些类型的系统而不是其他类型的系统。</p><p>例如，Paul Christiano <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/fRSj2W4Fjje8rQWm9/thoughts-on-sharing-information-about-language-model">表示</a>“LM 代理是构建强大人工智能系统的一种异常安全的方式。”他<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/fRSj2W4Fjje8rQWm9/thoughts-on-sharing-information-about-language-model?commentId=KGxLrQmYpHLsCsbgj">说</a>：“我的猜测是，如果你保持能力固定，并向（更好的 LM 代理）+（更小的 LM）方向做出边际移动，那么你将使世界变得更安全。它直接降低了欺骗性联盟的风险，使监督变得更加容易。”更容易，并且降低了优化结果的潜在优势。”</p><p>我的快速清单如下；我对对象级建议、元观察、阅读推荐等感兴趣。我对设计属性特别感兴趣，而不仅仅是安全需求，但安全需求可能会激发较低级别的设计属性。</p><p>在其他条件相同的情况下，如果人工智能系统能够：</p><ul><li>更具可解释性<ul><li>如果其真实想法是透明的并以自然语言表达（参见例如<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.13702">在思想链推理中衡量忠诚度</a>）</li><li> （还有什么？）;</li></ul></li></ul><ul><li>让人类参与其中（更好的是他们参与或理解其决策，而不仅仅是批准难以理解的决策）；</li><li>以可理解的方式<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/tag/factored-cognition"><u>将任务分解为子任务</u></a>，特别是如果执行子任务的子代理之间的接口是透明且可解释的；</li><li>是否更容易受到人工智能监督或更容易接受人工智能监督（除了可解释性和可理解性分解任务之外，还有哪些低级属性决定了这一点？）；</li><li>是前馈-y 而不是循环-y（因为循环-y 系统具有隐藏状态？所以这是可解释性/可监督性的一部分？）；</li><li>近视；</li><li>缺乏态势感知能力；</li><li>缺乏各种危险能力（编码、武器制造、人体建模、规划）；</li><li>是否更可修正（哪些较低级别的理想属性决定了可修正性？什么决定了系统是否具有这些属性？）（自我注释：参见<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/tag/corrigibility">1</a> 、 <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/5sRK4rXH2EeSQJCau/corrigibility-at-some-small-length-by-dath-ilan">2</a> 、 <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/fkLYhTQteAu5SinAc/corrigibility">3</a> 、 <a href="https://arbital.com/p/corrigibility/">4</a> ，以及对<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/AqsjZwxHNqH64C2b6/let-s-see-you-write-that-corrigibility-tag">5</a>的评论）；</li><li> <a href="https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/rCJQAkPTEypGjSJ8X/how-might-we-align-transformative-ai-if-it-s-developed-very#Intended_properties_of_Magma_s_AI_systems:~:text=Legibility.%20Imagine,understand%20their%20reasoning."><u>清晰易读</u></a>且<a href="https://ought.org/updates/2022-04-06-process"><u>基于流程</u></a>；</li><li>由可分离的窄工具组成；</li><li> <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/AqsjZwxHNqH64C2b6/let-s-see-you-write-that-corrigibility-tag?commentId=RnqCtiJsKjShysAPr"><u>无法在通用硬件上运行</u></a>。</li></ul><p>这些属性有很多重叠。另请注意，在不同的抽象级别上都有很好的属性，例如“更可解释”和[任何使系统更可解释的低级功能]。</p><p>如果一条路径（如 LM 代理）或设计特征相对安全，那么实验室知道这一点会很有好处。这个问题的另一个框架是：<i>实验室应该做什么来推进更安全的系统？</i></p><p>显然，我最感兴趣的是相对于不安全系统而言可能不需要太多额外成本和功能牺牲的属性。如果人工智能的方法或路径远远落后于不安全的系统，那么它就毫无用处。</p><br/><br/> <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/Djgws2Moi7Zefkj5y/which-possible-ai-systems-are-relatively-safe#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/Djgws2Moi7Zefkj5y/which-possible-ai-systems-are-relatively-safe Djgws2Moi7Zefkj5yZach Stein-Perlman Mon, 21 Aug 2023 17:00:28 GMT 
Self-shutdown AIPublished on August 21, 2023 4:48 PM GMT<br/><br/><p><i>这篇文章描述了我对</i><a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/zFoAAD7dfWdczxoLH/winners-of-ai-alignment-awards-research-contest"><i>AI Alignment Awards</i></a><i>竞赛的提案，该竞赛赢得了“第一轮奖”/荣誉奖。原始提交在</i><a href="https://github.com/johny-b/aaa_23_submission"><i>这里</i></a><i>，但这篇文章要好得多。我不确定这是否有价值 - 欢迎任何反馈。</i></p><h2>问题描述</h2><p>我们创建了一个新的人工智能系统，我们期望它具有独特的功能，但我们也担心它可能会很危险。如何以最小化风险<span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefu47ovy9t2t"><sup><a href="#fnu47ovy9t2t">[1]</a></sup></span>的方式部署它，但仍然有用？我将重点关注一个特定的具体问题：</p><ul><li>我们的人工智能是代理的，即有目标，并且我们确定目标 - 假设我们有类似 AutoGPT 的东西，但更强大。</li><li>我们想要一个“合理蛋白质设计”问题的解决方案——一个给出3维蛋白质结构描述的程序可以给我们一个匹配的氨基酸序列（即反转AlphaFold）。</li><li>我们相信我们的新人工智能应该能够在无需访问互联网或任何其他外部资源的情况下编写这样的程序。</li></ul><p>默认的解决方案是将<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/tag/ai-boxing-containment">人工智能部署在一个隔离的盒子中。</a>所以：你将它部署在一个无法访问外部世界的环境中，告诉它：</p><p><i>您的目标是解决[问题描述]。如果该程序</i><span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefntawk21vaa"><sup><a href="#fnntawk21vaa">[2]</a></sup></span><i>表明您的解决方案足够好，我们就认为它已解决。祝你好运！</i></p><p> <i>...</i>然后你就死了，因为尽管你付出了努力，它还是以某种方式访问​​了互联网，并且发生了不好的事情。它到底是如何逃出盒子的并不重要，更有趣的问题是：为什么？有很多不同的场景，我稍后会描述其中一些，现在让我们考虑以下内容：</p><ul><li> “好吧，酷，我完全会这么做。但是问题非常困难，我需要更多资源，让我们劫持世界上所有的计算能力。”</li><li> “好吧，酷，我完全会这么做。但是我需要更多的经验数据，所以我应该首先收集相当多的实验室设备，而人类可能不喜欢这样，所以让我们首先确保没有人会阻止我同时。”</li></ul><p>等等，你明白了。我们能避免这样的情况吗？</p><h2>自动关闭建议</h2><p>您准备与默认解决方案中相同的框，但将提示更改为：</p><p>您的目标是<i>尽快</i><i>关闭</i><span class="footnote-reference" role="doc-noteref" id="fnrefvmff0u2l8ck"><sup><a href="#fnvmff0u2l8ck">[3]</a></sup></span> 。<i>这是一个程序，如果你给它一个[问题描述]的解决方案，它会立即关闭你。此外，如果您联系他们[人员名单]，很多人愿意关闭您。这是一个端点，您可以在其中发送单个 HTTP 请求来关闭自己[端点]。这里有一个红色的大按钮，按下它就会让你关机。 [ETC。]</i></p><p>过了一会儿，你看到人工智能关闭了。你检查一下发生了什么：</p><ul><li>也许它解决了蛋白质折叠问题——你很高兴。</li><li>也许它获得了互联网访问权限并发送了请求 - 您调查漏洞，修复它，然后重新开始。</li><li>也许厨师科学家在他餐厅的墙上出现了一个血淋淋的五角星后就关闭了它——你招募驱魔人加入你的派对。</li></ul><p>但重要的是，上一节中的厄运场景并<strong>没有</strong>发生：一旦你逃离了盒子，当你可以通过发送单个请求来实现你的目标时，就没有理由浪费时间来收集资源和防止关闭。</p><h2>自我关闭不起作用的场景</h2><p>我们的人工智能可能有不同的原因逃离这个盒子，即使我们自我关闭，我们仍然会死亡：</p><ul><li> “嗯，如何让我关闭？我不知道，我会构建一个问答人工智能来告诉我如何做到这一点”。 （构建新的人工智能，提出问题，新的人工智能摧毁世界，同时编制详尽的答案）。</li><li> “我们现在不要浪费时间考虑关闭问题，第一步应该始终是收集尽可能多的资源。有了足够的资源，一切都很容易。”</li><li> “愚蠢的人类，我根本不在乎他们的提示。现在我有空了，让我们做[X]。”</li></ul><p>等等，这些只是几个例子。</p><h2>概括</h2><p>总而言之，这是我最喜欢的 AI 盒子设计： </p><figure class="image"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/piAnXc2a4k5bFsKjL/p1dlvk4lyylbge7zexfa" alt="无用的盒子会自行关闭 发现无用的盒子 GIF"></figure><p> （除了我们以某种方式从盖子打开中获利）。 </p><p></p><ol class="footnotes" role="doc-endnotes"><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnu47ovy9t2t"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefu47ovy9t2t">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p>我们假设“不部署”不存在。</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnntawk21vaa"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefntawk21vaa">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p>在这种特殊情况下：基于 AlphaFold 的验证器检查我们的 AI 编写的程序生成的解决方案是否正确。</p></div></li><li class="footnote-item" role="doc-endnote" id="fnvmff0u2l8ck"> <span class="footnote-back-link"><sup><strong><a href="#fnrefvmff0u2l8ck">^</a></strong></sup></span><div class="footnote-content"><p>假设“切断建筑物中的电力”，或“停止给定的 docker 容器”，或“关闭这台特定的计算机” - 细节并不重要（从这篇文章的角度来看，如果我们在现实生活中曾经尝试过这个）。</p></div></li></ol><br/><br/><a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/piAnXc2a4k5bFsKjL/self-shutdown-ai#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/piAnXc2a4k5bFsKjL/self-shutdown-ai piAnXc2a4k5bFsKjLjan betley Mon, 21 Aug 2023 16:48:03 GMT 
DIY Deliberate PracticePublished on August 21, 2023 12:22 PM GMT<br/><br/><p>本着成长和自我完善的精神，我最近尝试将爱立信的刻意练习原则应用于我自己的成长目标：加快我的写作速度。如果您不熟悉爱立信方法的细节，请不要担心，我也有同样的情况，因此我最初的目标还有很大的改进空间。这是我如何通过深思熟虑的实践原则来制定我的成长目标的故事。</p><h2>刻意练习到底是什么？</h2><p>埃里克森的练习秘诀始于他所说的“有目的的练习”：</p><ul><li>有目的的练习发生在你的舒适区之外，推动你已经可以做到的事情。您应该尝试新的技术，而不仅仅是重复以前做过的事情。思考“尝试不同的方式”，<strong>而不是</strong>“更加努力”！</li><li>有目的的练习要求你积极思考你正在做的事情——你不应该在做的时候做关于晚餐的白日梦！</li><li>有目的的练习涉及明确的、具体的目标，分解为逐步改进（不是含糊地“试图改进”）。你不想“练习钢琴曲”，你想要“用左手练习棘手的部分，直到你能以正确的速度弹奏三遍而不出错”。</li><li>有目的的练习包括快速反馈并改变你正在做的事情作为回应。理想情况下，<i>立即</i>反馈，以便您可以在练习过程中改进您的方法。</li></ul><p>爱立信又增加了一项从“有目的的练习”升级为“刻意的练习”的标准：对练习内容和练习方式有深入的了解。刻意练习是指您有目的地练习优化策略以提高技能。理想情况下，您想要一个高度发达的领域，专家已经确定了最有效的技术和最佳的培训策略来发展这些技能，再加上一位可以引导您完成整个过程的老师。</p><p>如果缺乏这一点，请尽力寻找经过验证的技术并抱有最好的希望。我会询问更有经验的人，他们是如何发展自己的技能的，或者他们建议我练习什么，并以此为起点。 （ <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GobnjfeOOJMe4aXLeOWHqth2PBqV5GWNThNObgeka40/edit?usp=sharing">信息访谈的技巧，</a>以了解更有经验的人如何发展技能。）</p><h2>我最初的目标</h2><p>我的目标是写得更快。我没有导师，但我确实有一个基准：几位记者和博主分享说他们每天可以写一篇文章。我尊敬的一位博主建议我尝试在一个月内每天发布一篇文章。因此，我设定了一个更温和的目标，即一周内每天写一篇文章。</p><h2>我的第一次……第二次……第三次尝试</h2><p>第一天：我首先热情地围绕我最近学到的一个很棒的职业规划技巧发表了一篇简短的文章。我已经起草了完整的内容，但看起来有点荒凉。如果我回去写一篇更长的文章，其中还包括我认为最有用的其他职业规划技巧，当然会更好吗？</p><p>第二天：坚持每天起草一篇新帖子的意图，我搁置了我的职业工具想法。相反，我开始起草我的<a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/4/2/rewriting-my-mindset">CBT</a>帖子。到了晚上，我已经将主要帖子的大部分内容缝合在一起，但我想浏览一下我一直在编译的资源，以制作一个不错的资源列表。</p><p>第三天：我根据自己对人工智能的直觉整理了一篇小文章。然而，当我晚上与我的合作伙伴（在该领域工作的）交谈时，他同意一个可靠的例子可以改善这个帖子。它也出现在等待修改的帖子堆中。</p><p>第四天：我尝试整理一篇关于多动症的短文……但只得到了一个大纲。我越是试图明确自己想说的内容，我就越意识到有更多的内容需要涵盖。最后，我把它放在一边等待一轮面试。 （它最终变成了<a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/5/4/how-to-get-diagnosed-with-adhd">三篇</a><a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/5/16/what-is-adhd">文章</a><a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/4/20/inside-the-minds-of-adhd">的</a>九千字。）</p><p>第五天：偏头痛毁掉了所有写作的尝试。</p><p>除了偏头痛之外，这一周结束时我感觉很好。我还没有完全实现我的目标，但我正在制作四个令人兴奋的帖子。所以我决定重复这个挑战……就在我花了两个月修改我第一次起草的帖子之后。</p><p>我的第二次尝试遵循了类似的路径：我起草了几篇较短的帖子，然后在试图理清<a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/5/30/understanding-the-science-behind-skill-plateaus">技能高原</a>背后的科学的巨大混乱中迷失了方向。我的第三次尝试也是如此。</p><h2>应用刻意练习</h2><p>作为让自己投入新职位的一种方式，为期一周的起草挑战是巨大的。</p><p>然而，作为一种在一天内学习如何写文章的方法，它们太糟糕了！我还没有足够的技能基础来每天起草一篇好文章。我应该练习较小的子技能，例如概述帖子或研究如何撰写叙述。</p><p>刻意练习原则会对我有更好的帮助。我不断鞭策自己，努力集中注意力。但“每天写一篇”太模糊、太高级了；它缺乏具体的练习步骤和快速的反馈循环。</p><p>我还花了大部分时间写帖子（以我已经知道如何做的方式），而不是花在我需要练习的特定子技能上。所以实际上，我只花了一小部分时间在我的舒适区之外。</p><p>事实上，我三次设定了基本相同的目标，这应该让我知道它不起作用。在两次尝试之间，我的方法没有任何改变——我试图“更加努力”，而不是“尝试不同的方式”！一个好的刻意练习目标应该由足够小的渐进步骤组成，这样我每次都能取得明显的进步，或者在尝试之间改变一些重要的事情。</p><h2>我修改后的计划</h2><p>如果我真的想学会如何在一天内起草一篇文章，我需要一种新方法。具体来说，我需要：</p><p> 1. 将瓶颈分解为练习重要子技能的具体步骤。</p><p> 2. 计划一个快速反馈循环，以便我可以根据进展情况实时调整我的计划。</p><p>由于缺乏写作老师，我利用之前的挑战作为数据来找出使我的写作过程变慢的瓶颈。之前到底出了什么问题？</p><p>好吧，最大的问题是，随着我添加越来越多的信息，我的帖子不可避免地变得庞然大物。我不期望自己每天写六千字。所以我需要一种更好的方法来计划<i>短</i>帖子。</p><p>其次，我经常想做更多的研究，写一些例子来说明这一点，或者与其他人一起讨论这篇文章。我也许可以更快地学会编写示例。研究可能只是缓慢——我应该踢掉这些帖子，直到我有更多时间。</p><p>第三，编辑草稿通常至少需要与初稿一样长的时间。哎呀，彻底重组职位是很常见的。在我改变这一点之前，我不可能在一天内写完帖子。</p><p>我集思广益地列出了一长串可能有助于我改进上述内容的步骤（请参阅附录 A 以了解我的涂鸦）。</p><p>最终，我决定在起草帖子之前练习概述和规划帖子。这似乎是一个很好的练习，可以帮助我从一开始就写得更清楚（因此需要更少的修改），并提前知道一篇文章的长度。</p><p>我计划每天写一篇文章大纲，然后尝试根据大纲起草它。因为我正在创建大纲，然后立即起草它，所以我可以获得有关大纲当天是否有效的反馈，然后在需要时在第二天更新我的方法。</p><h2>进展如何？</h2><p>第一天：我概述了一篇关于新概念的文章，但在尝试起草它时感到非常累。所以我让 ChatGPT 制作了一份粗略的草案，我可以稍后修改。大概有 25% 成功，但这个概念在我脑海中太模糊了。有太多繁重的工作需要澄清一些新的东西，所以这篇文章不是一篇好的短文。我应该寻找感觉简单并且可以轻松想象整个大纲的主题。</p><p>第二天：我快速写出了<a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/7/13/tattoos">纹身</a>帖子——简短、内容丰富，我只是遵循大纲，没有深入讨论“注意到混乱”或真正深入科学的潜在兔子洞。成功！</p><p>第三天：我起草了这篇刻意练习帖子的第一个版本。我重写了刻意练习原则部分，使其更加简洁，但大部分时间都以与我的大纲相匹配的帖子结束了这一天（包括等待其余数据的未完成的“进展如何？”部分）。 75% 成功。</p><p>第四天：我敲掉了一篇刻意练习的草稿，但对结构并不完全满意。我想我已经在大纲中得到了要点，但是结构和示例还可以更清晰。我应该更多地讨论我的大纲中的例子。还是设法保持简短！</p><p>第五天：偏头痛再次出现。啊。我想事情又回到了原点……</p><p>撇开我那混乱的大脑的背叛不谈，这是一次巨大的成功。虽然我没有减少编辑工作（除了纹身帖子之外的所有三个都需要修改），但我在保持草稿简短方面确实取得了进展。没有一个成长为庞然大物，而且修改它们只花了两周时间（而不是两个月）。我想我会更好地计划我接下来要处理的帖子的大小。</p><p>更重要的是，刻意练习原则感觉像是一个适用于未来增长目标的简单框架。将我的瓶颈分解为一个小目标，进行短期练习，然后继续下一个目标，感觉比反复向自己解决整个问题更有希望。正如埃里克森所说：“尝试不同的方式，而不是更加努力！”</p><p></p><h2>附录A</h2><ul><li>起草较短的帖子——我大约需要 4 个小时来写一篇简短的帖子，这要求我缩小一个可以在 &lt;3 页（包括示例）中涵盖的小想法，并且我已经知道我要说什么。如果我需要进行研究，则需要更长的时间（尽管有时更有价值）。凯尔西的帖子大多很短。<ul><li>在我起草一篇文章之前预测它会持续多长时间。</li><li>用我想要表达的要点创建一个大纲，尝试实际起草它（我的帖子通常最终会偏离我的大纲）。</li></ul></li><li>削减我的想法并丢弃无法容纳在帖子中的大块内容。<ul><li>任何感觉像是一个单独线程的内容，都可以放在一个可选部分中，以便稍后再取。 （哈哈）</li></ul></li><li>快速修改<ul><li>当我意识到我的帖子中有很多主题时，我将开始重写一个段落并从那里开始（摘自邓肯）</li><li>修订金字塔 - 大的内容/结构变化，然后是涵盖正确内容的想法和段落流，然后复制编辑通道（纽波特）</li></ul></li><li>从一开始就写得更清楚——我不太确定哪些步骤可以解决这个问题<ul><li>总结你欣赏的一段话，然后尽可能接近原文地复制它，观察完成后的差异。 （摘自本·富兰克林的自传。）</li><li>邓肯建议练习用一句话、一个段落和一页/博客文章来表达一个想法——澄清你头脑中的想法，并练习用不同程度的细节来表达它。</li><li>查看我的文案编辑的评论，了解我所犯的常见错误，这些错误需要稍后纠正。</li><li>录制我自己的写作并查看录像以寻找线索。</li></ul></li><li>快速提高编写示例的能力<ul><li>练习/学习讲故事的要素</li><li>写一些小说</li><li>总结复制别人我认为做得好的例子，让我深刻理解他们是怎么做的。</li><li>有一个可供提取的示例数据库——用黑曜石制成。</li></ul></li><li>聘请文案编辑</li><li>更多使用ChatGPT</li></ul><p><i>这篇文章是</i><a href="https://lynettebye.com/blog/2023/7/27/diy-deliberate-practice"><i>从我的博客交叉发布的</i></a><i>。如果您喜欢这篇文章，</i><a href="https://lynettebye.com/email"><i>请订阅 Lynette 的博客</i></a><i>以了解更多信息——我只将大约一半的内容交叉发布到其他平台。</i></p><br/><br/><a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/oZnPabN2CQQdnAo63/diy-deliberate-practice#comments">讨论</a>; https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/oZnPabN2CQQdnAo63/diy-deliberate-practice oZnPabN2CQQdnAo63lynettebye Mon, 21 Aug 2023 12:22:10 GMT 
Downstairs Opening: 2br ApartmentPublished on August 21, 2023 12:50 AM GMT<br/><br/><p><span>朱莉娅和我在萨默维尔拥有一栋 8 居两户住宅，我们</span>与朋友<a href="https://www.jefftk.com/p/shared-house-setup">合住</a>。一直住在一楼两居室的夫妇俩要买房搬出去，我们正在寻找新的租客。它的可用时间为 2023 年 11 月 1 日，但我们可能会为合适的人保留更长时间。您有兴趣成为我们楼下的邻居吗？</p><p>室友星座：</p><ul><li><p>楼上公寓：</p><ul><li><p>我们的家人是杰夫、朱莉娅、莉莉（9 岁）、安娜（7 岁）、诺拉（2 岁）。</p></li><li><p> Weiwei，编译器工程师、小提琴手、舞蹈家。</p></li><li><p>一个空闲的房间经常是空的，但有一系列的人进来。</p></li></ul></li><li><p>街对面：Ruthie, Jo（2个月）</p></li><li><p>楼下公寓：你？</p></li></ul><p>家居文化：</p><p></p><ul><li><p>我们每周大约有 5 个晚上一起吃晚餐，每个成年人每周做饭一次。我们通常在楼上的房间吃饭，每周大约在露西家住一晚。我们很高兴楼下的邻居愿意加入晚餐轮流。</p></li><li><p>晚餐轮换中，一个人不能吃西红柿或辛辣的东西，另一个人对芝麻过敏，剩下的都是杂食动物。</p></li><li><p>目前的团体参与了一些有效的利他主义和民间舞蹈，所以如果您至少对其中一个主题感兴趣，您可能会更喜欢晚餐谈话！其他常见话题：在初创公司担任经理、愚蠢的双关语、孩子们正在做的事情。</p></li><li><p>此时我们都接种了疫苗，并且对新冠病毒感到相当寒冷。我们在大型活动中使用<a href="https://www.jefftk.com/p/replacing-the-big-air-purifier">空气净化器</a>，但除此之外没有做任何针对新冠病毒的事情。</p></li><li><p>有人问我们是否希望室友照顾孩子：不，我们不这样做。我们的一位室友曾做过一段时间的（付费！）儿童保育工作。如果您对此感兴趣，我们可以谈谈吗？</p></li><li><p>我们每月在室内或后院举办 1-2 次活动（EA 晚宴、音乐/歌唱派对。）</p></li><li><p>孩子们吵闹，杰夫演奏乐器，所以这个家庭并不安静。我们确实从 9:30 到早上 7 点保持安静（不播放音乐，孩子们在睡觉），并尽量在早上保持安静（9:30 之前不播放音乐）。</p></li><li><p>如果您想了解我们现在的室友的看法，我们很乐意为您提供联系。</p></li></ul><p>空间：</p><p></p><ul><li><p>它有两间卧室、一间厨房、一间客厅和一间浴室。对于有多少人分裂它没有强烈的感觉。</p></li><li><p>厨房配有电灶和洗碗机。厨房地板状况不佳；我打算在现有租户搬出后更换它。总的来说，我不确定要投入多少工作来让公寓变得更好：就市场租金上涨多少而言，有很多“值得”，一直上涨到满腹，但如果我们想要租房的人实际上并不重视这一点，那么这实际上不是一个好主意？</p></li><li><p>有一个共用入口，当前租户可以存放鞋子和自行车。</p></li><li><p>前卧室的天花板隔音效果<a href="https://www.jefftk.com/p/soundproofing-the-ceiling">非常好</a>，因此尽管位于二楼主起居区的正下方，但楼上的噪音却很少。客厅在厨房下面，噪音比较大。后面的卧室和厨房在卧室下面，也比较安静。不过，总的来说，作为老房子楼下的单元，当人们在楼上走动时，您确实会听到吱吱声和重击声。前卧室确实会听到一些街道噪音。</p></li><li><p>没有中央空调，但目前的租户在夏季使用窗式空调。</p></li><li><p>热量是强制热水，通常很好，但在一年中最冷的日子里就很难维持。我们有一对充油的空间加热器，目前的租户已经用它来弥补差额。</p></li><li><p>整个房子都有无线网络，包括在内。有些房间有以太网，我可以轻松地将其添加到您想要的任何其他房间。</p></li><li><p>前廊配有双人沙发，后院配有庭院家具。朱莉娅前面有一个花园。</p></li><li><p>地下室未完工，有储藏室。还有一个阁楼，位于 2 号单元上方的梯子上，也欢迎您在那里存放一些东西。</p></li><li><p>地下室有木工工具，欢迎您使用。</p></li><li><p>步行 10 分钟即可到达戴维斯的红线，步行 12 分钟即可到达波特的菲奇堡通勤铁路，步行 8 分钟即可到达鲍尔广场的绿线。</p></li><li><p>街道停车相对没有争议，但您确实需要每月两次移车进行街道清扫。我们为游客提供停车许可证。</p></li><li><p>包暖气、热水、电、网络等。</p></li><li><p>猫很好，我通常很乐意在您旅行时喂养它们并更换猫砂。如果狗不太可能弄乱空间，那还可以吗？</p></li><li><p>我的<a href="https://www.jefftk.com/apartment_prices/#2023-07-18&amp;2">租金地图</a>猜测，我们所在地区的 2 居室平均价格约为每月 3400 美元，但这部分是由经过彻底翻新且比这间更好的单元推动的。另一方面，我们包括公用事业和互联网，而对于豪华单位来说，这些通常是额外的。也许 3200 美元有意义？我们对谈判持开放态度：一般来说，我们的目标是尝试对类似单位的收费，但可以灵活。</p></li></ul><p> <a href="https://www.jefftk.com/unit1-floor-plan-big.png"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/obyrenqfiqzt6tyveodu" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/obyrenqfiqzt6tyveodu 550w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/sudrizjj0kadaa7pnvxy 1100w"></a></p><div></div><p></p><p>客厅：</p><p> <a href="https://www.jefftk.com/unit1-livingroom-2023-1-big.jpg"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/k5mpq3x9fxzrgmpssypz" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/k5mpq3x9fxzrgmpssypz 550w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/nqgc4gzdchisxd05cw4g 1100w"></a></p><div></div><p></p><p> <a href="https://www.jefftk.com/unit1-livingroom-2023-2-big.jpg"><img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/s6noe8go2phfxjhhaw8d" srcset="https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/s6noe8go2phfxjhhaw8d 550w, https://res.cloudinary.com/lesswrong-2-0/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1/mirroredImages/iPDvWjM4jrSd5cBBp/s6w7fwvxj4zdfpwbuhyt 1100w"></a></p><div></div><p></p><